#: ../../../source/docs/porting/asyncify.rst:5
msgid "Asynchronous Code"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/porting/asyncify.rst:7
msgid ""
"Emscripten supports two ways (Asyncify and JSPI) that let **synchronous** C "
"or C++ code interact with **asynchronous** JavaScript. This allows things "
"like:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/porting/asyncify.rst:10
msgid ""
"A synchronous call in C that yields to the event loop, which allows browser "
"events to be handled."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/porting/asyncify.rst:12
msgid ""
"A synchronous call in C that waits for an asynchronous operation in JS to "
"complete."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/porting/asyncify.rst:15
msgid ""
"In general the two options are very similar, but rely on different "
"underlying mechanisms to work."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/porting/asyncify.rst:18
msgid ""
"`Asyncify` - Asyncify automatically transforms your compiled code into a "
"form that can be paused and resumed, and handles pausing and resuming for "
"you, so that it is asynchronous (hence the name \"Asyncify\") even though "
"you wrote it in a normal synchronous way. This works in most environments, "
"but can cause the Wasm output to be much larger."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/porting/asyncify.rst:23
msgid ""
"`JSPI` (experimental) - Uses the VM's support for JavaScript Promise "
"Integration (JSPI) for interacting with async JavaScript. The code size will "
"remain the same, but support for this feature is still experimental."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/porting/asyncify.rst:27
msgid ""
"For more on Asyncify see the `Asyncify introduction blogpost <https://"
"kripken.github.io/blog/wasm/2019/07/16/asyncify.html>`_ for general "
"background and details of how it works internally (you can also view `this "
"talk about Asyncify <https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=qQOP6jqZqf8>`_). The "
"following expands on the Emscripten examples from that post."
msgstr ""

